{
  "text": "The tau-leap method generates approximate sample paths efficiently by taking time-steps of length \u03c4 through time, and firing multiple reactions during each time-step. We will work with a fixed choice of time-step, \u03c4 . During each time-step, the key assumption we make is that the reaction propensities are constant. It can then be shown that the number of times that reaction channel R j fires during each time-step is a Poisson random variate, with known parameter [CITATION_1] . By repeatedly advancing by a time-step of length \u03c4 through time 2 , a sample path can be generated.",
